1325":"1325","1320":"1320","1353":"1353","1382":"1382","1409":"1409","1381":"1381","2 February 1409":"2 February 1409","1428":"1428","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":33,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Didbrok was born in 1349, in Bristol, Gloucestershire, England, his father, Adam de Didbrok, was 29 and his mother, Mrs Adam Didbrok, was 25. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. Robert Didbrok. He died on 2 February 1409, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1349–2 February 1409":"1349–2. veebruar 1409","1349–1409":"1349–1409","1353–Female":"1353–Surnud","1381–1428":"1381–1428","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1349":"1349","1325":"1325","1320":"1320","1353":"1353","1382":"1382","1409":"1409","1381":"1381","2 February 1409":"2. veebruar 1409","1428":"1428","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"1349–2 February 1409":"1349–2. helmikuuta 1409","1349–1409":"1349–1409","1353–Female":"1353–Kuollut","1381–1428":"1381–1428","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1349":"1349","1325":"1325","1320":"1320","1353":"1353","1382":"1382","1409":"1409","1381":"1381","2 February 1409":"2. helmikuuta 1409","1428":"1428","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England"},"fr":{"1349–2 February 1409":"1349–2 février 1409","1349–1409":"1349–1409","1353–Female":"1353–Décédée","1381–1428":"1381–1428","1320–Male":"1320–Décédé","1325–Female":"1325–Décédée","1349":"1349","1325":"1325","1320":"1320","1353":"1353","1382":"1382","1409":"1409","1381":"1381","2 February 1409":"2 février 1409","1428":"1428","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Robert de Didbrok est né en 1349, à Bristol, Gloucestershire, Angleterr